1 Introduction

The method of Pethő [8] (see also [5]) gives a fast algorithm to calculate ”small” solutions of Thue equations. The method is based on the continued fraction algorithm. By ”small” solutions we mean those with absolute values less than, say 10500superscript10500NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:500 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end10^{500}. Nobody belives that such equations have larger solutions. All our experiences show that such equations usually only have a few very small solutions.

In this paper we make this algorithm more efficient in order to calculate ”small” solutions of a special type of Thue equations, the binomial Thue equations of type

xn-m⁢yn=±1⁢in⁢x,y∈ℤ.formulae-sequencesuperscript𝑥𝑛𝑚superscript𝑦𝑛plus-or-minus1in𝑥𝑦ℤitalic-x POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start italic-n POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end ADDOP:minus italic-m italic-y POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start italic-n POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end RELOP:equals ADDOP:plus-or-minus NUMBER:1 in italic-x PUNCT:, italic-y RELOP:element-of blackboard-Z PERIOD:.x^{n}-my^{n}=\pm 1\;\;{\rm in}\;\;x,y\in{\mathbb{Z}}. (1)

Using sharp estimates and utilizing the specialities of these equations we perform an extensive calculation by a high performance computer to determine solutions with max⁡(|x|,|y|)<10500𝑥𝑦superscript10500OPFUNCTION:maximum OPEN:( VERTBAR:| italic-x VERTBAR:| PUNCT:, VERTBAR:| italic-y VERTBAR:| CLOSE:) RELOP:less-than NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:500 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end\max(|x|,|y|)<10^{500} of binomial Thue equations for 1<m<1071𝑚superscript107NUMBER:1 RELOP:less-than italic-m RELOP:less-than NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:7 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end1<m<10^{7} (assuming that the left hand side is irreducible) for the exponents n=3,4,5,7,11,13,17,19,23,29𝑛3457111317192329italic-n RELOP:equals NUMBER:3 PUNCT:, NUMBER:4 PUNCT:, NUMBER:5 PUNCT:, NUMBER:7 PUNCT:, NUMBER:11 PUNCT:, NUMBER:13 PUNCT:, NUMBER:17 PUNCT:, NUMBER:19 PUNCT:, NUMBER:23 PUNCT:, NUMBER:29n=3,4,5,7,11,13,17,19,23,29. Our data contains all solutions of these equations with high probability. These results complete several results on the solutions of binomial Thue equations [3], [2], [7].

3 Computational aspects

We were executing the algorithm of [8] with C=10500𝐶superscript10500italic-C RELOP:equals NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:500 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:endC=10^{500} for n=𝑛absentitalic-n RELOP:equalsn= 3, 4, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29 (the case n=4𝑛4italic-n RELOP:equals NUMBER:4n=4 was dealt with in [6]) using the above sharp estimates that made the procedure for binomial Thue equations much more efficient. This efficient algorithm allowed us to perform the calculations for all those 2≤m≤1072𝑚superscript107NUMBER:2 RELOP:less-than-or-equals italic-m RELOP:less-than-or-equals NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:7 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end2\leq m\leq 10^{7} for which the left side of (1) is irreducible.

The procedure was implemented in Maple [4], we used 1200 digits accuracy. For each exponent this calculation involved almost 107superscript107NUMBER:10 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:start NUMBER:7 POSTSUPERSCRIPT:end10^{7} binomial Thue equations. The routines were running on the supercomputer (high performance computer) network situated in Debrecen-Budapest-Pécs-Szeged in Hungary under Linux. For each exponent the total running time was about 120-200 hours calculated for a single node which yields a few hours using parallel computing with a couple of nodes.
